04244nam a22006495i 9781846151057DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20012001xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97818461510577 a10.1515/97818461510572doi  a(DE-B1597)676003  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 7aLCO0110002bisacsh04a943.71/022/09221 aKlassen, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Letters of the Rozmberk Sisters :bNoblewomen in Fifteenth-Century Bohemia /cJohn Klassen, Eva Dolezalová, Lynn Szabo.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2001] 1bD.S.Brewer, c[2001] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (144 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLibrary of Medieval Women00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tPreface -- tIntroduction. The Rožmberk Family in Fifteenth-Century Bohemia -- tThe Correspondence of Perchta and Anéžka of Rožmberk -- tInterpretive Essay. Self and Family in the Letters of Perchta of Rožmberk -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWomen in 15c Bohemia express themselves on marriage, companionship, daily castle life, and family relations.The letters of the Rozmberk sisters, Perchta and Anézka, give a vivid insight into how medieval women viewed themselves. Perchta's letters inform her father that his choice of a husband for her has caused her desperate sadness andsorrow in which death seems a better alternative. Despite her unhappiness and her almost total dependence on others, however, Perchta undertook to take control of her own fate and to improve the circumstances of her life. Her letters were the means whereby she informed her father and brothers of her misery and persuaded them to take action, and in the process they tell us about her expectations of respect and companionship in marriage. The letters of bothsisters show them to be women with a vigorous sense of their own dignity and offer insights into the hopes and disappointments, joys and vexations of fifteenth-century women. The letters also introduce theenvironment and the activities of daily castle life, and offer an intimate picture of family life in the fifteenth century.JOHN M. KLASSEN is Professor of History at Trinity Western University, Canada. He was assisted in the translations by EVA DOLEZALOVA, Historical Institue, Prague, and LYNN SZABO, Trinity Western University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFamiliesvSourcesxHistoryy15th centuryzCzech RepubliczBohemia. 4aEast European Studies. 4aMedieval History. 4aMedieval Literature. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Letters.2bisacsh  aBohemia.  aCastle life.  aFamily relations.  aFifteenth-Century.  aMarriage.  aNoblewomen.  aWomen's perspectives.1 aDolezalová, Eva, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSzabo, Lynn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781846151057?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846151057423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846151057/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles